%
'Twas the new moon!
Since then I waited—
And lo! to-night!
[I have my reward].

        -- Matsuo Basho (1644-1694)
%
On a withered branch
A crow is sitting
This autumn eve.

        -- Matsuo Basho (1644-1694)
%
An ancient pond!
With a sound from the water
Of the frog as it plunges in.

        -- Matsuo Basho (1644-1694)
%
'Tis the first snow—
Just enough to bend
The gladiolus leaves!

        -- Matsuo Basho (1644-1694)
%
A cloud of flowers!
Is the bell Uyeno
Or Asakusa?

        -- Matsuo Basho (1644-1694)
%
I come weary,
In search of an inn—
Ah! these wisteria flowers!

        -- Matsuo Basho (1644-1694)
%
The cry of the cicada
Gives us no sign
That presently it will die.

        -- Matsuo Basho (1644-1694)
%
Of Miidera
The gate I would knock at--
The moon of to-day.

        -- Matsuo Basho (1644-1694)
%
Ah! the waving lespedeza,
Which spills not a drop
Of the clear dew!

        -- Matsuo Basho (1644-1694)
%
Even in the rain, come forth,
O midnight moon!
But first put on your hat.

        -- Yamazaki Sokan (1465-1553)
%
Thought I, the fallen flowers
Are returning to their branch;
But lo! they were butterflies.

        -- Arakida Moritake (1472-1549)
%
For all men
'Tis the seed of siesta--
The autumn moon.

        -- Matsunaga Teitoku (1562-1645)
%
'Tis the cuckoo—
Listen well!
How much soever gods ye be.
%
'Tis the first snow,
Yet some one is indoors—
Who can it be?
%
The club-shaker's
Rising and falling in the water
Until it becomes a musquito.
%
O ye fallen leaves!
There are far more of you
Than ever I saw growing on the trees!
%
Alas! the width of this musguito-net
Which meets my eye when I wake
And when I lie down.
%
